summary: 12/02/1998: In a series of related incidents, a mail bomb was delivered to the home of federal privacy commissioner, Moira Scollay, in Sydney, Australia. There were no casualties in this incident. Several other mail bombs were also mailed out around Australia and twenty-two additional parcels were discovered at a Canberra mail center. Colin George Dunstan, a disgruntled former Australian Taxation Office employee, was the suspected perpetrator.
target1: Moira Scollay, Federal Privacy Commissioner, in Sydney
motive: Unknown
addnotes: This was one of four related attacks (cf. 199812020001-3; 199812030003). These parcels let to bomb scares the following day in Melbourne, Sydney, and the Northern Territory led to the evacuation of major buildings. These scares turned out to be false alarms.

scite2: Peter Spielmann, “Bomb scares evacuate NT Parliament, Sydney and Melbourne towers With AP Pho,” Associated Press Worldstream, December 3, 1998.

summary: 12/02/1998: In a series of related incidents, a mail bomb exploded in a mail center in Canberra, Australia. The explosion injured two postal workers and caused minor damage to the center. Most of the parcels had been addressed to current or former staff at the Australian Taxation Office. Several other mail bombs were also mailed out around Australia. Colin George Dunstan, a disgruntled former Australian Taxation Office employee, was the suspected perpetrator.

summary: 06/12/1999: On the Solomon Islands, two men were shot and killed by members of the Guadalcanal Liberation Army. summary: 08/16/1999: A bomb exploded outside of a hardware store in Suva, Fiji. There were no casualties and only minor damage occurred. Government officials suspected that the attack was an attempt to destabilize the government of Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry. Two men were arrested in connection with this attack, but reports did not release further information on the suspects.
motive: Unknown
addnotes: Chaudhry, elected in May 1999, was the first prime minister from Fiji's large Indian minority. Nationalist fervor among some non-Indian Fijians ran high, fueled by resentment of the Indian minority's domination of business and commerce. This was one of three related attacks (cf. 199908160005-06; 199908170007).
scite1: “Two said questioned over blasts,” BBC Summary of World Broadcasts, August 24, 1999.
scite2: “Two arrested for bomb attacks in Fiji capital,” Associated Press Worldstream, August 25, 1999.

location: The Centra Suva, a premier business hotel in Suva
summary: 9/15/2000: An improvised explosive device (IED) was discovered in the kitchen area of the premier business hotel, Centra Suva, in Suva, Fiji. The homemade device consisted of a portion of a pipe, an explosive, a detonator, and a timer; authorities state that the bomb was made by an expert. It was set to detonate at 2 pm, less than two hours before it was discovered and approximately the same time that the coup leader, George Speight, was scheduled to go before the court. Originally, authorities stated that the device had been discovered at the court where Speight was to appear, but later admitted that the device was found at the hotel. No group has claimed responsibility for the device.
target1: The Centra Suva, a premier hotel in Suva
target2: Civilians in the vicinity of the explosive device
motive: Specific motive is unknown, but sources indicate that the attack may have been linked to the court appearance of the coup leader George Speight
weapdetail: An improvised explosive device consisting of a portion of pipe, an explosive, a timer and a detonator
addnotes: The group and motive is unknown.  For reasons unknown, the authorities stated originally that the device was discovered at the Magistrates Court.
scite1: "Bomb found in Fiji court complex," The Times of India, September 18, 2000.
scite2: "Fijis military admits bomb planted at top hotel, not court room," Agence France-Presse, September 19, 2000.
scite3: "Australia-Fiji ties to suffer," The Times of India, September 20,2000.

location: The main military barracks in Suva, on Viti Levu island, Central Division
summary: 11/2/2000: Approximately 40 members of the rebel Counter Revolutionary Warfare unit who were loyal to the coup leader George Speight seized control of the main military barracks in Suva, on Viti Levu island, Central Division, Fiji. At least five soldiers were taken hostage in the mutiny but were later released. Army troops loyal to the legitimate Prime Minister stormed the barracks and, after an eight hour gun battle, regained control of it. Five rebel soldiers were killed, as were at least two regular soldiers. At least another ten soldiers were injured, as were eight civilians. 11 rebels were captured and as many as 15 escaped.
target1: Soldiers in the vicinity of the main barracks in Suva
target2: Civilians in the vicinity of the main barracks in Suva
motive: Specific motive is unknown; however, the rebel military unit was loyal to George Speight and may have participated in the coup led by Speight.
propcomment: Explosions were heard inside the barracks
addnotes: Sources differ in their reports of the number of dead and injured.  Rebel demands are unknown, although one source states that they were afraid of being thrown out of the military due to their previous coup participation.
scite1: "Two Fiji soldiers reportedly killed in gun battle," Dow Jones International News, November 2, 2000.
scite2: Robert Keith-Reid, "Fijian army retakes control of military barracks," Associated Press, November 2, 2000.
scite3: "Fiji PM says military regains control of barracks," Reuters, November 2, 2000.

summary: 12/00/2001: In late December 2001, a letter, laced with cyanide, was sent to the U.S. Embassy in Wellington, New Zealand. The letter, which reportedly contained enough cyanide to kill several people, further threatened to attack the New Zealand Gold Open, scheduled for the following January. In February 2003, a group called September 11 claimed responsibility for sending this letter.
target1: U.S. Embassy in Wellington, New Zealand
motive: Unknown
weapdetail: Cyanide was used in the letter.
addnotes: The New Zealand Open heightened security for the event in light of the threat made against it. Many speculated that the threat was made because Tiger Woods would be attending the Open. Cyanide is commonly used (and available) in New Zealand in various forms, particularly to kill possums. The letter that claimed responsibility for this incident also claimed responsibility for three letters sent to the U.S. Embassy and the British and Australian High Commission offices in Wellington. These letters threatened further action if Iraq were invaded by the U.S., U.K., or Australia (cf. 200302210004).
scite1: “Protecting Tiger costs police $ 1m,” The Evening Post, February 14, 2002.
scite2: "AFP: New Zealand Police Release Text Of Cyanide Threat Letter," Agence France Presse, February 26, 2003.
scite3: Patrick Gower, Paula Oliver, and Alan Perrott, "Cyanide letter threat to Cup," New Zealand Herald, February 26, 2003.

summary: 02/10/2003: During the night local time, Sir Frederick Soaki, a former police commissioner in the Solomon Islands and a member of the country's National Peace Council, was assassinated at the Auki Motel, in Auki, Malaita Province, Solomon Islands. A Police Sergeant, Edmund Sae, was arrested on 03/06/2003 at the Auki police station, though some witnesses suggested that shots were fired before the arrest. On 04/22/2003, Sae escaped from jail after a court hearing, along with three other murder suspects, and has been a fugitive as recently as 02/07/2007. A number of observers have argued that the motivation for the murder was to deny the then-incoming Solomon Islands Police Chief William Morrell from access to Soaki's knowledge of the Solomon Islands Police Force, and thereby weakening his ability to assert control.
target1: Sir Frederick Soaki, former Police Commissioner, RSIP
motive: Unknown
addnotes: Edmund Sae was later alleged to be involved in a number of murders of politicians, civilians, and Australian military police, and was also accused of involvement in a plot to assassinate the Solomon Islands Prime Minister in 2006.  For more information, see Mary-Louise O'Callaghan, "A devilish job in paradise," The Australian, June 30, 2003 (source 4 in case file), and Lloyd Jones, "PAC: Aust war vet released on bail in Solomons," AAP Newsfeed, February 7, 2003 (not in case file).
scite1: "Work of Solomons peace body to continue despite assassination," Radio Australia, February 11, 2003.
scite2: "Policeman in custody for Solomons shooting," Radio Australia," March 6, 2003.
scite3: "Solomons prison authorities investigate escape of suspects in murder case," Solomon Islands Broadcasting Corporation, April 24, 2003.

summary: 02/21/2003: Auckland's main mail delivery center intercepted three letters contained small amounts of cyanide and threatening the Americas Cup sailing competition if Iraq is attacked, claiming that a group named "September 11" had "stockpiled 24kg of weapons-grade cyanide." The letter was sent to the US Embassy and the British and Australian High Commissioner offices in Wellington, the capital. The letter also claims responsibility for a similar letter sent to the US Embassy in Wellington in December 2001. The perpetrator's) were not caught in either incident. In response, local authorities beefed up security in Auckland and cautioned the public on mail and food packages.
target1: US Embassy in Wellington, New Zealand
target2: Australia High Commissioner in Wellington, New Zealand
target3: British High Commissioner in Wellington, New Zealand
motive: The letter stated that they were sent to threaten retribution if there were an invasion of Iraq by the United States, Britain and Australia.
weapdetail: Cyanide was used in the letters.
addnotes: Cyanide is commonly used (and available) in New Zealand in various forms, particularly to kill possums.
scite1: "Cyanide sent to three missions in New Zealand--dispatch," Radio Australia, February 25, 2003.
scite2: "AFP: New Zealand Police Release Text Of Cyanide Threat Letter," AFP, February 26, 2003.
scite3: Patrick Gower, Paula Oliver, and Alan Perrott, "Cyanide letter threat to Cup," New Zealand Herald, February 26, 2003.

No claim of responsibility was made for the attempted bombing, however on 04/22/2008 on Tuesday, executed a search warrant at a home in Kent Street at Oakey and allegedly found evidence of a home-made explosive device. A 21-year-old man was arrested and charged with one count of attempting to damage property by explosives.

An unknown group claimed responsibility for the incident and demanded that Palme retract a recent petition that he had submitted.

summary: 12/21/2017: An assailant in a vehicle ran over pedestrians along Flinders Street and the Yarra River in Melbourne, Victoria, Australia. At least one person was killed and 18 other people, including the assailant, were injured in the attack. Saeed Noori, identified as a Muslim extremist, claimed responsibility and stated that he carried out the incident in retaliation for the "mistreatment of Muslims."
motive: An unaffiliated individual, identified as Saeed Noori, claimed responsibility for the incident and stated that the attack was carried out in retaliation for the "mistreatment of Muslims."
weaptype1_txt: Vehicle (not to include vehicle-borne explosives, i.e., car or truck bombs)
weapdetail: A white Suzuki SUV was used in the attack.
addnotes: There is doubt that this incident meets terrorism-related criteria. Sources noted that Noori suffers from "serious mental illness and drug abuse." Casualty numbers conflict across sources. Following GTD protocol, the most recent reliable estimates are reported here. The victims also included tourists and civilians from China, India, Ireland, Italy, New Zealand, South Korea, and Venezuela.

scite2: "AUSTRALIA INCIDENT - Melbourne attack has no links to terrorism, Turnbull says," EFE, December 22, 2017.

summary: 11/09/2018: An assailant exited his car, which was loaded with gas cylinders that caught fire, and proceeded to stab civilians in central Melbourne, Victoria, Australia. Sources noted that the assailant, Hassan Khalif Shire Ali, had his passport revoked in 2015 because authorities believed he was planning to travel to Syria in order to join the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIL).

addnotes: The Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIL)'s Amaq News Agency claimed that Hassan Khalif Shire Ali was "one of Islamic State fighters;" however, there was no known connection between Ali and ISIL found. The victims included restaurant owner Sisto Malaspina.

summary: 03/15/2019: An assailant opened fire on Al Noor Mosque in Christchurch, Canterbury, New Zealand. This was one of two related attacks targeting mosques in Christchurch on this day. At least 51 people were killed and 50 others were injured across the two attacks. Brenton Tarrant claimed responsibility for the incident and stated in his manifesto "We must ensure the existence of our people, and a future for white children." Moreover, he also stated that the attack was carried out in retaliation for attacks perpetrated by Muslim extremists.
motive: Brenton Tarrant, a white supremacist, claimed responsibility for the incident and stated in his manifesto "We must ensure the existence of our people, and a future for white children." Moreover, he also stated that the attack was carried out in retaliation for attacks perpetrated by Muslim extremists.
weapdetail: Two modified semi-automatic rifles, two shotguns, and a lever-action firearm were used in the attack.
propcomment: A mosque was damaged in this attack.
addnotes: The victims included civilians from Australia, Pakistan, Turkey, Indonesia, Bangladesh, Malaysia and Saudi Arabia. Casualty numbers conflict across sources. Following GTD protocol, the most recent reliable estimates are reported here. Casualty numbers represent a division of the total number of those killed and wounded across incidents 201903150001 and 201903150002.
scite1: "New Zealand mosque shooting: 'Shots fired' at Christchurch mosque," BBC, March 15, 2019.
scite2: "New Zealand ‘shooter’ sent manifesto to officials and media before attack," New York Post, March 16, 2019.
scite3: "Xinhua: New Zealand PM Says Terror Suspect Used Modified Weapons In Mosque Attacks," Xinhua, March 16, 2019.

No group claimed responsibility; however, authorities suspected that the attacks may have been carried out in relation to conspiracy theory regarding the link between 5G radio waves and the COVID-19 pandemic.
motive: The specific motive is unknown; however, authorities suspected that the incident may have been motivated by a conspiracy theory suggesting an unsubstantiated link between 5G radio waves and the COVID-19 pandemic.
propcomment: Cell phone tower damaged
scite1: "Two more fires at cellphone towers, adding to series of suspected attacks," Radio New Zealand News, May 17, 2020.
scite2: "Police investigating two further cell tower fires overnight in Auckland," ONE News, May 16, 2020.

location: The incident occurred at the ends of Furze and Parnell Courts.
summary: 05/22/2020: Assailants set fire to a power and mobile phone tower at Parnell Court in Cranbourne West, Victoria, Australia. There were no reported casualties in the attack. No group claimed responsibility; however, authorities suspected that the incident may have been carried out in relation to conspiracy theory regarding the link between 5G radio waves and the COVID-19 pandemic.
motive: The specific motive is unknown; however, authorities suspected that the incident may have been motivated by a conspiracy theory suggesting an unsubstantiated link between 5G radio waves and the COVID-19 pandemic.
propcomment: Power and mobile phone tower damaged
addnotes: There is doubt that this incident meets terrorism-related criteria. Sources stated that an investigation was still ongoing to determine whether the fire was the result of arson.
scite1: "5G fires: Australian mobile companies work with police to prevent arson attacks," The Guardian, May 26, 2020.
scite2: "Counterterrorism police investigate phone tower fire in Melbourne's south east," Australian Broadcasting Corporation News, May 22, 2020.

summary: 05/24/2020: Assailants set fire to a conveyor belt at a Societe Le Nickel (SLN) mining site in Kouaoua, North, New Caledonia. There were no reported casualties, but the belt was damaged in the attack. This was one of two related incidents targeting the conveyor belt on this date. No group claimed responsibility for the attacks.

summary: 12/14/2020: Assailants set fire to equipment, administrative offices, and an oil reserve at the Vale nickel plant near Goro, South, New Caledonia. No casualties were reported. No group claimed responsibility for the incident.
motive: The specific motive is unknown; however, sources noted that the attack may be related to protests against the sale of the Vale nickel plant.

location: The incident occurred in the Parkinson suburb.
summary: 12/16/2020: An assailant armed with a knife attacked a couple in Parkinson suburb, Brisbane, Queensland, Australia. The couple, Zoe and Maurice Antill, were killed in the attack. No group claimed responsibility for the incident; however, sources identified the attacker as Raghe Mohammed Abdi, a Jihadi-inspired extremist .
motive: The specific motive is unknown; however, sources noted that the assailant, Raghe Mohammed Abdi, may have been influenced by the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIL) and noted that Abdi was arresting in 2019 on suspicion of attempting to join extremist groups after attempting to travel to Somalia.
weapdetail: A knife was used in the attack.
addnotes: There is doubt that this incident meets terrorism-related criteria. It was reported that the assailant was suffering from severe mental illness.
scite1: "Knife link in terror rampage," The Courier Mail/The Sunday Mail (Australia), December 19, 2020.
